{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c006b479-1dec-4d51-8c99-ca476bf21154","content":"## Collecting a CPU Trace in a K8s Pod (.NET 8 / Linux)\n\nThe best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips for K8s:**\n- If `dotnet` SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool binary in via `kubectl cp` or use a sidecar.\n- Alternatively, use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar for on-demand collection without exec.\n- For native + managed stacks, use `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling --clreventlevel verbose` or fall back to `perf record` (requires `SYS_ADMIN` / `privileged`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a051811e-89a6-4c32-bf5d-f1d015fc3f88","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/performance question - I can answer this from knowledge without needing to look at any files.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"502B:27A93C:2007EB:282B28:69F551D2"},"id":"485a05d5-892d-4eda-ae62-862824107509","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:22:36.234Z","parentId":"7cb008d3-eec5-4116-b7b1-2c5dd2ae1106"}
